{
  id:"muttaburrasaurus", name:"Muttaburrasaurus", epithet:"M. langdoni", pron:"MUT-ah-BUR-ah-SAW-rus",
  period:"cretaceous", clade:"Rhabdodontomorph ornithopod (basal iguanodontian)", diet:"herbivore",
  age:"~96 Ma (mid-Cretaceous, Cenomanian)", startMa:100, endMa:93, length:"~7 m", mass:"~2.8 t", place:"Queensland, Australia",
  img:"images/species/muttaburrasaurus.jpg",
  overview:"A large-bodied ornithopod from the mid-Cretaceous of central Queensland, Muttaburrasaurus is among the most skeletally complete dinosaurs known from Gondwana and is Queensland's official fossil emblem. It carried an unusual, hollow, upward-bulging bony swelling above the snout, and its exact place on the ornithopod family tree has shifted across several competing analyses since its 1981 description. A 2026 re-study of the original holotype using CT, neutron, and synchrotron scanning substantially revised what is known of its skull and feeding habits.",
  insights:[
    ["A snout built to be picky, not indiscriminate","Unusually large olfactory bulbs and distinctive tooth-wear patterns, identified in a 2026 re-study, point to <b>selective feeding on preferred plants</b> rather than the indiscriminate bulk grazing long assumed of large ornithopods."],
    ["A bump nobody can fully explain","The hollow nasal swelling (bulla nasalis) has been read as a smell-enhancing chamber, a sound-resonating structure, or a visual display feature. No fossilised soft tissue survives to settle it, so <b>the debate remains open on anatomy alone</b>."],
    ["Sixty years, three new imaging technologies","The holotype was collected in 1963 and described in 1981, then left largely unrevisited until 2026, when CT, neutron scattering, and synchrotron imaging revealed internal skull structures never previously described - a reminder that <b>old specimens can still be new evidence</b>."],
    ["Nobody agrees where it belongs","Competing phylogenetic analyses have placed Muttaburrasaurus as an elasmarian, a styracosternan, a rhabdodontid, a rhabdodontomorph, and a dryosaurid's sister taxon. The instability reflects how <b>little of the skull was originally described in detail</b>, not a shortage of specimens."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Muttaburrasaurus browsed low-to-mid vegetation - ferns, cycads, and conifers - in a mid-Cretaceous Queensland landscape bordering the inland Eromanga Sea, sharing its world with small ornithopods, early birds, and megaraptoran theropods. Its powerful jaw musculature and shearing cheek teeth suggest it could process tougher plant material than many contemporaries, and the 2026 re-study's evidence of selective feeding implies an animal targeting particular plants rather than clearing vegetation indiscriminately.</p><p>Whether it lived in groups remains unconfirmed; multiple individuals are known from the same region and geological interval, which is consistent with gregarious behaviour but does not by itself demonstrate it.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Muttaburrasaurus sits within the basal iguanodontian radiation, at a level of the ornithopod tree that produced very different outcomes on different continents: in the Northern Hemisphere this grade led toward <b>Iguanodon</b> and eventually the hadrosaurs, while in Gondwana it produced a separate radiation of rhabdodontomorphs and elasmarians that never crossed into hadrosaur-style dental batteries. Its precise position within that Gondwanan radiation is still argued over, making it a genuine test case for how ornithopods diversified once Gondwana began to fragment.</p>",
  study:[
