    material:["Partial skull","Lower jaws","Vertebrae","Partial pelvis","Limb elements","Isolated teeth"],
    note:"The holotype (QM F6140) was found by grazier Doug Langdon in 1963 and formally described by Bartholomai and Molnar in 1981, but the skull's original description was superficial by modern standards, which has confounded decades of attempts to resolve its phylogenetic position. A 2026 re-study (Herne et al.) reworked the original holotype quarry, identified previously undescribed elements of the holotype skull, and applied CT, neutron scattering, and synchrotron imaging to reconstruct the braincase, nasal passages, and endocranium in detail - substantially revising the animal's inferred diet and sensory biology. The same study used U/Pb dating of detrital zircons at the holotype locality to place its age at 96.3 (plus or minus 8.6) million years, in the Cenomanian; older literature had generally treated the holotype as Albian in age, several million years earlier, so the animal's precise place in the Cretaceous timeline has itself recently shifted. The referred 'Dunluce' skull, from slightly older rock, shows a shorter nasal swelling than the holotype, which may reflect age, individual variation, or a distinct population."
