{
  id:"minmi", name:"Minmi", epithet:"M. paravertebra", pron:"MIN-my",
  period:"cretaceous", clade:"Basal ankylosaur", diet:"herbivore",
  age:"~121-112 Ma (Early Cretaceous, Barremian-Aptian)", startMa:121, endMa:112, length:"~3 m", mass:"~300 kg", place:"Queensland, Australia",
  img:"images/species/minmi.jpg",
  overview:"A small, lightly armoured ankylosaur from the Early Cretaceous of Queensland, Minmi was the first ankylosaur described from the Southern Hemisphere. It lacked a tail club and skull armour entirely, but carried unusual bony rods alongside its vertebrae - the paravertebrae that give it its species name - along with rare belly armour absent in most of its relatives. A more complete skeleton long shown in documentaries and museum casts under the name Minmi was reassigned to a new genus, Kunbarrasaurus, in 2015.",
  insights:[
    ["The skeleton most people picture isn't this one","A near-complete skeleton found near Richmond, Queensland, was preliminarily assigned to Minmi and widely reproduced in books and documentaries. In 2015 it was formally split off as a new genus, <b>Kunbarrasaurus</b>, leaving true Minmi known only from its more fragmentary holotype."],
    ["Armour where it's rarely needed","Minmi had bony plates protecting its belly, a feature largely absent in other ankylosaurs, which typically armoured only the back and flanks. This suggests a <b>predation risk from below or beside</b>, not only from above."],
    ["A last meal preserved in stone","Plant material - ferns, seeds, and fruit - was found in the position of the stomach in one specimen, giving <b>direct evidence of diet</b> rather than an inference from tooth shape alone."],
    ["Bony rods with no settled purpose","The paravertebrae - thin ossified rods running alongside the vertebrae - are unique to this genus among ankylosaurs. They probably stiffened the back or supported muscle attachment, but their exact mechanical role is <b>still being worked out</b>."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Minmi was a small, low-browsing herbivore of Early Cretaceous floodplains and woodlands, at a time when part of Queensland formed an island separated from the rest of Australia. Its long legs relative to its small armoured body have prompted suggestions that it could move faster than most ankylosaurs, potentially outrunning some threats rather than relying on armour alone - though this remains an inference from limb proportions rather than direct trackway evidence.</p><p>Preserved gut contents identify a diet of ferns, seeds, and fruit, giving Minmi one of the more direct dietary records among Cretaceous armoured dinosaurs.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Minmi is currently regarded as a basal ankylosaur, positioned outside the split between the two major later lineages, Ankylosauridae (club-tailed) and Nodosauridae (club-less, heavier flank armour). Its combination of features - no tail club, no skull armour, ventral armour, and unique paravertebrae - does not map cleanly onto either group, making it a useful data point for understanding what the earliest ankylosaurs looked like before that split occurred. The genus's isolation on Cretaceous Australia, separated from other continents as Gondwana broke apart, also makes it relevant to arguments about how ankylosaurs reached the Southern Hemisphere at all.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"Was the well-known 'Minmi' skeleton really Minmi?",
     why:"A near-complete skeleton was assigned to the genus based on limited shared features before a fuller description was possible.",
     interps:[
       ["A distinct genus (Kunbarrasaurus)","conf-strong","A 2015 formal description found sufficient anatomical differences from the Minmi paravertebra holotype to justify a new genus, now the accepted classification."],
       ["A second Minmi species","conf-low","The original, more cautious referral treated the specimen as Minmi sp.; this view has been superseded by the 2015 redescription but illustrates how provisional identifications can persist in popular sources."]
