  matters:"Minmi is a useful corrective for anyone picturing 'the' Australian ankylosaur: the detailed, camera-ready skeleton most people have seen belongs to a different genus entirely. What's left under the name Minmi is smaller, more fragmentary, and stranger - unique bony rods, belly armour, and no tail club - a reminder that a genus name and a famous skeleton don't always refer to the same animal.",
  fossilRecord:{
    knownFrom:"Holotype QM F10329 (partial skeleton with paravertebrae, ribs, pelvis, femur, and armour) from the Bungil Formation; additional fragmentary material from the Allaru Mudstone and Toolebuc Formation, Queensland",
