  overview:"A massive short-necked pliosaur from the Early Cretaceous Eromanga Sea that once covered much of inland Australia, Kronosaurus is known for a skull that could exceed two metres in length, armed with large conical teeth suited to crushing rather than slicing. A famous 1959 mounted skeleton at Harvard's Museum of Comparative Zoology, long the public face of the animal, is now known to have been reconstructed with several extra vertebrae, inflating its apparent length by roughly a quarter over current estimates - and the mounted specimen's own generic identity is itself the subject of an active, unresolved naming dispute.",
  insights:[
    ["A skeleton stretched by plaster","The 1959 Harvard mount, for decades the animal's public image, included <b>seven to eight extra vertebrae added during reconstruction</b>, inflating its length to a widely repeated 12.8 metres. Current estimates place the real maximum closer to 9-10.5 metres."],
    ["A skull that dwarfs a T. rex's","Even at revised body-length estimates, Kronosaurus skulls reach roughly the same length as an adult human is tall, and comfortably exceed the skull size of the largest known theropod dinosaurs - a genuine record among Mesozoic predators, no exaggeration required."],
    ["Teeth built to crush, not carve","Its conical teeth lack cutting edges, unlike the blade-like teeth of related pliosaurs such as Liopleurodon, pointing to a <b>crushing bite</b> suited to prey like ammonites and other marine reptiles rather than a slicing predatory style."],
    ["The name itself is under dispute","A 2022 study argued the original holotype material is too fragmentary to anchor the name Kronosaurus, proposing the famous Harvard skeleton be reassigned to a new genus entirely. Other researchers have since defended the traditional name. <b>Which name properly applies to which specimen remains unresolved</b> - the animal's existence isn't in question, only its label."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Kronosaurus was an apex predator of the Eromanga Sea, powering itself with four broad flippers in the same underwater-flight style as other pliosaurs, rather than the fish-like tail undulation of ichthyosaurs. Its skull-to-body proportions and blunt, robust teeth suggest a diet including hard-shelled prey such as ammonites alongside other marine reptiles, favouring a crushing bite over the slashing style of narrower-toothed relatives.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Kronosaurus belongs to Pliosauridae, the short-necked, large-headed branch of Plesiosauria, within a subgroup (Brachaucheninae) that produced some of the largest marine predators of the Cretaceous. Its close relatives include other giant Cretaceous pliosaurs found on different continents, part of a broader pattern of pliosaurs repeatedly evolving toward maximal skull and body size across the Mesozoic before disappearing well before the end-Cretaceous extinction, ceding the apex marine-predator role to mosasaurs.</p>",
