  overview:"A small stegosaur from the Late Jurassic Tendaguru Formation of Tanzania, Kentrosaurus carried a double row of plates along its neck and shoulders that transitioned into long, sharp paired spikes down its back, hips, and tail. Excavated by German expeditions before the First World War from a bonebed representing dozens of individuals, most of the original material was destroyed in the bombing of Berlin during the Second World War, leaving the animal's detailed anatomy dependent on pre-war records, photographs, and the roughly one third of specimens that survived.",
  insights:[
    ["Small cousin, same design","Kentrosaurus is roughly half the length of its better-known relative <b>Stegosaurus</b>, found on a different continent in a similar time window - a close relative doing the same basic job of armoured, low-browsing herbivore, just at a smaller scale."],
    ["A whip with a point","Detailed biomechanical modelling of the tail's range of motion and muscle attachment shows it could deliver <b>seriously dangerous strikes</b> to a predator, supporting the long-standing assumption that the tail spikes were an active weapon rather than passive armour."],
    ["A quarry, not a specimen","The main Tendaguru quarry preserved bones from an estimated <b>fifty or more individuals</b>, allowing study of individual variation between what are now interpreted as slender and robust morphs - most likely reflecting sex or age differences rather than separate species."],
    ["A war fought twice with the same fossils","Much of the original holotype and referred material was destroyed when Allied bombing burned the Berlin Museum für Naturkunde in the Second World War. What survives today is a <b>patchwork of pre-war documentation and the roughly one third of specimens that escaped destruction</b> - a rare case of a fossil record damaged twice, once by geology and once by history."]
