  behaviour:"<p>Kentrosaurus was a slow-moving, low-browsing herbivore of a semi-arid, seasonally wet Late Jurassic coastal landscape, sharing its ecosystem with giant sauropods and large theropod predators. Unable to outrun a determined attacker, it relied on its spiked tail as an active defensive weapon: biomechanical modelling of its range of motion and muscle leverage indicates the tail could be swung with enough force and precision to seriously injure an attacking predator, rather than serving only as a visual deterrent.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Kentrosaurus belongs to Stegosauridae, and despite being found on a different continent from <b>Stegosaurus</b>, several recent phylogenetic analyses recover it as a fairly close relative within the family rather than a primitive outlier - a pattern consistent with stegosaurs having a broad Pangaean-to-early-Gondwanan distribution before continental separation restricted lineages to their own landmasses. Its plate-to-spike transition down the body is a variant on the same basic stegosaur armour plan seen from <b>Huayangosaurus</b> in China through to Stegosaurus in North America.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"What was the tail spike arrangement really used for?",
