    evidenceLevel:"Rich",
    locality:"Tendaguru, Lindi Region, Tanzania",
    formation:"Tendaguru Formation (Middle and Upper Saurian Beds)",
    material:["Vertebrae","Ribs","Pelvis","Limb bones","Plates and spikes","Partial skull elements"],
    note:"Kentrosaurus was collected during the German Tendaguru Expedition of 1909-1913, led by Werner Janensch, and formally described by Edwin Hennig in 1915 from a lectotype specimen. The scale of the original haul - over 1,200 bones representing dozens of individuals - made it one of the best-sampled stegosaurs of its time. Most of this material was destroyed when the Museum für Naturkunde in Berlin was bombed during the Second World War; roughly a third of the original collection survived, supplemented by detailed pre-war photographs, drawings, and descriptions that allow the destroyed material to still inform current study. Because armour elements were rarely found in direct articulation with the skeleton, the precise arrangement of plates and spikes along the body is reconstructed from a combination of the few articulated finds and comparison with better-preserved relatives."
