  insights:[
    ["A giant, revised downward twice","The original 2001 description estimated a maximum length of 11-12 metres using scaling equations from living gharials and saltwater crocodiles. A 2019 re-analysis, using equations developed specifically for <b>long-snouted forms</b>, revised this down to roughly 9-9.5 metres - still enormous, but a substantially different animal on paper."],
    ["A generalist among specialists","Unlike most of its close pholidosaurid relatives, which were narrow-snouted fish specialists in marginal marine settings, Sarcosuchus thrived in <b>freshwater river systems</b> and shows jaw and tooth features suited to tackling large land vertebrates as well as fish."],
    ["No death roll available","A 2014 biomechanical study concluded Sarcosuchus's body proportions made the modern crocodilian 'death roll' unlikely, meaning it must have used <b>different techniques</b> to subdue and dismember large prey than living crocodilians do."],
    ["Growth rings tell a fifty-year story","Bone microstructure analysis of the growth rings in its skeleton suggests individuals could live for <b>fifty to sixty years</b>, reaching maximum size only after decades of continued growth - a lifespan far exceeding most living crocodilians."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Sarcosuchus was an ambush predator of Early Cretaceous river systems, its bulbous snout tip (a narial bulla) possibly aiding in bellowing or intimidation display, in a manner not unlike unrelated hollow-crested dinosaurs of the same era. Its broad diet, encompassing fish and large land vertebrates including dinosaurs that ventured near the water's edge, is supported by tooth and jaw morphology adapted to a generalist role rather than the narrow piscivory typical of its closest relatives.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Sarcosuchus belongs to Pholidosauridae, a family of crocodyliforms mostly known as slender-snouted marine or coastal piscivores; its comparatively robust build and generalist ecology mark it as an outlier within its own family, illustrating that even a tightly related group of crocodile-line reptiles could diversify well beyond a single dietary strategy. Its scale places it among a small handful of the largest crocodyliforms ever to have lived, alongside far later and unrelated giants such as the North American Deinosuchus.</p>",
