    note:"Sarcosuchus material was first collected during French expeditions to the Sahara between 1946 and 1959, but the genus was not formally named until 1966, based on a nearly complete skull. A major 2001 expedition led by Paul Sereno recovered additional skulls and skeletal material spanning several growth stages, enabling detailed study of anatomy, growth rate, and longevity, and producing the original 11-12 metre size estimate through comparison with living long-snouted crocodilians. A second species, S. hartti, is known from Brazil, indicating the genus or a close relative had a transatlantic distribution while South America and Africa remained connected or narrowly separated. Later reanalysis (O'Brien et al., 2019) applied different allometric equations more appropriate to extremely long-snouted forms, producing the current, more conservative size estimate."
