  age:"~200-183 Ma (Early Jurassic, Hettangian-Pliensbachian)", startMa:200, endMa:183, length:"~6 m", mass:"~1 t", place:"South Africa; Lesotho; Zimbabwe",
  img:"images/species/massospondylus.jpg",
  overview:"A basal sauropodomorph from the Early Jurassic of southern Africa, Massospondylus was among the first dinosaur genera ever named, described by Richard Owen in 1854 from fragmentary material. It is known from an exceptional range of growth stages, from the oldest confirmed dinosaur embryos yet found to fully grown adults, and this ontogenetic series has become a central battleground for a long-running and still-unsettled question: whether hatchlings moved on all fours before adopting the bipedal stance seen in adults.",
  insights:[
    ["Among the first dinosaurs ever named","Massospondylus was described in 1854, only a few decades after the word 'dinosaur' itself was coined, making it one of the <b>earliest-named dinosaur genera</b> still considered valid today."],
    ["The oldest nursery on record","Multiple clutches of eggs containing embryos, first found in 1976 at Golden Gate Highlands National Park, remain the <b>oldest confirmed dinosaur embryos</b> known, preserving body proportions from before hatching."],
    ["A famous hypothesis, now seriously contested","A widely cited 2005 study proposed hatchlings were obligate quadrupeds that shifted to bipedalism as adults grew. More recent studies of vestibular anatomy and limb proportions have <b>argued against this shift</b>, while a further 2025 study argued for it again - a live disagreement, not a settled textbook fact."],
    ["No teeth at birth","Near-hatchling embryos show no fully developed teeth, suggesting young Massospondylus could not immediately feed themselves and may have <b>depended on parental care</b> in their earliest days - itself an inference from anatomy rather than direct behavioural evidence."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Massospondylus was a herbivore, and possibly an occasional omnivore, browsing vegetation in a semi-arid Early Jurassic landscape across what is now southern Africa. Adults are generally reconstructed as facultatively or fully bipedal, walking on their hind legs with a long neck and small head suited to reaching foliage, though the posture of hatchlings and how quickly it changed through growth remains an active point of disagreement between different lines of anatomical evidence.</p><p>At least ten nesting sites are known from Golden Gate Highlands National Park alone, suggesting the same nesting ground was reused across multiple generations - a rare window into dinosaur reproductive behaviour this early in the group's history.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Massospondylus belongs to the basal sauropodomorph grade that also includes <b>Plateosaurus</b> and <b>Mussaurus</b> in this collection, the lineage that would eventually give rise to the giant quadrupedal sauropods of the Jurassic and Cretaceous. Its embryonic material has been used to test a specific evolutionary hypothesis: that sauropod quadrupedality evolved partly by retaining juvenile, forelimb-heavy body proportions into adulthood, a process called paedomorphosis. Whether Massospondylus itself shows an early version of this pattern is exactly the point under current dispute.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"Did Massospondylus hatchlings move on four legs before becoming bipedal as adults?",
     why:"Embryonic and hatchling material shows body proportions very different from adults, but different anatomical methods for inferring posture have reached conflicting conclusions.",
     interps:[
       ["Quadrupedal hatchlings, bipedal adults","conf-moderate","The original 2005 description and a 2025 study of embryonic and hatchling material both support a genuine locomotor shift through growth, based on limb and body proportions."],
       ["No true shift in stance through growth","conf-moderate","More recent studies of vestibular (inner ear) anatomy and forelimb-to-hindlimb robusticity ratios have argued the proposed shift is not supported once these additional lines of evidence are considered."]
