    formation:"Elliot Formation",
    material:["Embryos in ovo","Hatchling skeleton","Juvenile and adult skeletons","Egg clutches","Neotype skeleton"],
    note:"Massospondylus carinatus was named by Richard Owen in 1854 from fragmentary material; because the original type material was too poor for confident comparison, a neotype skeleton was formally designated in 2019 to stabilise the name. Embryos were first found in 1976-1978 by James Kitching at Golden Gate Highlands National Park but were too fragile to extract with the technology available at the time; they were fully prepared and described only in 2005, by which point they represented the oldest dinosaur embryos then known. At least ten nesting horizons are documented at the same site, each with multiple clutches. A 2025 study using additional embryonic and hatchling specimens reopened the debate over ontogenetic changes in stance, following intervening studies that had challenged the original 2005 hypothesis."
