  age:"~162 Ma (Late Jurassic, Oxfordian)", startMa:163, endMa:161, length:"~24-26 m (neck alone ~14.4-15.1 m)", mass:"~15-25 t", place:"Xinjiang, China",
  img:"images/species/mamenchisaurus.jpg",
  overview:"A sauropod genus spanning several named species across Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous China, Mamenchisaurus is defined by necks that made up close to half the total body length. The best-studied species, M. sinocanadorum, is known from only a handful of bones, yet a detailed 2023 re-analysis used that limited material to establish the longest neck confidently measured for any sauropod. Recent phylogenetic work has also found that the genus, as currently used, does not represent a single natural group.",
  insights:[
    ["The longest neck properly measured, not just claimed","A 2023 CT-based re-analysis of M. sinocanadorum's sparse remains - three neck vertebrae, a rib, and skull fragments - established a neck length of <b>14.4 to 15.1 metres</b>, the longest that can currently be confidently supported for any sauropod species."],
    ["A neck built mostly from air","CT scanning found the cervical vertebrae were <b>69-77% air by volume</b>, comparable to the lightweight skeletons of storks. To stop such a hollow structure from being too fragile, cervical ribs over four metres long ran alongside the neck, bundling together to stiffen it."],
    ["Bigger numbers exist, but rest on shakier ground","Figures of 35 metres and 60-80 tonnes are widely repeated for this species, but trace back to two <b>undescribed vertebrae</b> whose species identity has not been confirmed - a different, and far less certain, kind of evidence than the peer-reviewed neck measurement."],
    ["One genus, several family trees","Recent phylogenetic analyses (2020-2025) find that Mamenchisaurus, as currently defined, is <b>not a single natural group</b> - different named species land in different parts of the sauropod tree. Researchers have kept the genus name for practical reasons while acknowledging a full taxonomic revision is overdue."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Mamenchisaurus browsed vegetation across a wide horizontal arc without needing to move its body, an energy-efficient feeding strategy suited to its neck's length. A biomechanical study of the neck's rib structure found it was likely too stiff to be raised vertically like a giraffe's, unlike the more flexible necks of diplodocids such as Diplodocus - suggesting Mamenchisaurus fed mostly at low to middle heights by sweeping its head sideways rather than reaching upward.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Mamenchisaurus belongs to Mamenchisauridae, a lineage of basal eusauropods that pushed neck length to an extreme independently of the diplodocoid and macronarian lineages responsible for other long-necked giants in this collection, such as Diplodocus and Brachiosaurus. Extreme sauropod necks evolved at least four separate times across different lineages, and Mamenchisaurids were among the first to do so, making the group an important early test case for how such a body plan could work mechanically before later, unrelated sauropods arrived at similar solutions.</p>",
  study:[
