  matters:"Mamenchisaurus is a case study in separating a verified scientific result from the much bigger number that tends to travel further. The peer-reviewed 14.4-15.1 metre neck is a genuine record, carefully reconstructed from a handful of bones - but the 35 metre, 60-80 tonne figures that circulate alongside it rest on different, unconfirmed material. The genus is also a reminder that a convenient shared name doesn't guarantee a real evolutionary grouping underneath it.",
  fossilRecord:{
    knownFrom:"At least six named species with varying completeness; M. sinocanadorum known only from a partial skull and three neck vertebrae with an associated cervical rib",
    evidenceLevel:"Partial",
    locality:"Sichuan Basin, China (most named species); Junggar Basin, Xinjiang (M. sinocanadorum)",
    formation:"Upper Shaximiao Formation (Sichuan species); Shishugou Formation (M. sinocanadorum)",
    material:["Neck vertebrae","Cervical ribs","Partial skulls","Dorsal and caudal vertebrae","Limb elements"],
    note:"Mamenchisaurus was first discovered in 1952 at a highway construction site in Sichuan and named in 1954 by C. C. Young, who intended to honour the discovery site, Mamingxi ('horse-neighing brook'), but mistakenly wrote a different, non-existent place name, Mamenxi, which became permanently fixed in the genus name. M. sinocanadorum was discovered in 1987 in the Junggar Basin, Xinjiang, by the joint China-Canada Dinosaur Project, and formally named in 1993. A 2023 re-analysis by Moore and colleagues used CT scanning of the original material to reconstruct neck length, vertebral pneumaticity, and cervical rib structure in detail. Phylogenetic analyses published between 2020 and 2025 have consistently found the genus to be non-monophyletic, with a comprehensive taxonomic revision still outstanding."
  },
