  overview:"A small, early tyrannosauroid from the Early Cretaceous of Liaoning, Dilong provided the first direct fossil evidence that tyrannosaurs had feathers, described from filamentous protofeather impressions preserved near the jaw and tail. At barely two metres long, it stands in stark contrast to its much later, giant relative Tyrannosaurus, illustrating how far the group's body size shifted over its evolutionary history.",
  insights:[
    ["The first proof tyrannosaurs had feathers","A 2004 description identified <b>filamentous protofeather impressions</b> near the jaw and tail of one specimen, the first direct fossil evidence that any member of Tyrannosauroidea carried feathers rather than scales alone."],
    ["A fox-sized ancestor of a giant lineage","At around two metres long, Dilong is one of the smallest known tyrannosauroids, a striking contrast with its much larger relative <b>Tyrannosaurus</b>, tens of millions of years later - a reminder that the group did not start out as apex-sized predators."],
    ["Feathers at both ends of the size range","Dilong shows insulating filaments at a small body size; the much larger, later <b>Yutyrannus</b> in this collection shows similar feathers at a body size around nine metres long. Together they undercut any simple assumption that feathers belonged only to small or juvenile tyrannosauroids."],
    ["A skull ahead of its body","Dilong's skull already shows features shared with advanced, later tyrannosaurids, while its body - three-fingered hands, comparatively long arms - retains a more primitive coelurosaur build. The two halves of its skeleton were <b>evolving at different rates</b>."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Dilong was a small, lightly built predator likely hunting lizards, small vertebrates, and early mammals across the fern and conifer-covered landscape of Early Cretaceous Liaoning, alongside the other feathered dinosaurs and early birds of the Jehol Biota. Its protofeathers - short, branched filaments unlike true flight feathers - were unsuited to flight and most likely functioned as insulation, consistent with an active, warm-blooded lifestyle rather than the sluggish behaviour associated with cold-blooded reptiles.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Dilong sits near the base of Tyrannosauroidea, well below the split that eventually produced the giant derived tyrannosaurids in this collection - Tyrannosaurus, Albertosaurus, Daspletosaurus, Gorgosaurus - all of which lost the long arms and three-fingered hands still present in Dilong. Its mix of an advanced, tyrannosaurid-like skull with a primitive coelurosaur body illustrates that the lineage's later, more familiar body plan was assembled gradually, feature by feature, rather than appearing all at once.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"Did feathers belong to tyrannosauroids of every size, or only small and juvenile individuals?",
