    material:["Nearly complete skeleton (holotype)","Skull elements","Protofeather impressions","Referred skulls and postcranial material"],
    note:"Dilong was described by Xu Xing and colleagues in 2004 in Nature, in a paper that also established the first direct evidence of protofeathers in Tyrannosauroidea. The holotype individual is thought, based on bone texture, to represent a juvenile, so the adult size of around two metres is an estimate rather than a direct measurement. Protofeather impressions are preserved only around the jaw and tail region of one specimen; whether feathers covered the whole body is not directly confirmed by the fossil evidence itself."
