  age:"~67-66 Ma (latest Maastrichtian)", startMa:67, endMa:66, length:"~8-9 m", mass:"~750 kg", place:"Jiangxi, China",
  img:"images/species/qianzhousaurus.jpg",
  overview:"Nicknamed 'Pinocchio rex' on its 2014 description, Qianzhousaurus was a long-snouted tyrannosaurid from the very end of the Cretaceous in southern China, standing in sharp contrast to the deep, thick-toothed skulls of relatives such as Tyrannosaurus and Tarbosaurus. It belongs to Alioramini, a distinct branch of long-snouted tyrannosaurids also including Alioramus from Mongolia, and its fully fused skull settled early questions about whether such an unusual proportion could simply reflect a juvenile animal.",
  insights:[
    ["Not a juvenile - a specialist","Early scepticism suggested the long snout might just belong to a young individual of a deep-skulled species. A detailed 2021 redescription found the skull's cranial sutures <b>fully fused</b>, with bone texture matching mature tyrannosaurid individuals, ruling out the juvenile explanation directly."],
    ["A nose over a third longer than expected","Qianzhousaurus's snout makes up roughly 70% of its skull length, around <b>35% longer</b> than proportionally similar deep-snouted tyrannosaurids, paired with narrow teeth quite unlike the thick, bone-crushing teeth of Tyrannosaurus."],
    ["Sharing the top of the food chain","A smaller, deep-snouted relative, Asiatyrannus, was described from the same region in 2024. The different skull shapes and body sizes of the two animals suggest <b>different hunting strategies and prey preferences</b>, allowing two large predators to coexist without direct competition."],
    ["One of the last dinosaurs standing","Dated to the very end of the Maastrichtian, Qianzhousaurus was <b>among the final tyrannosaurids</b> to exist before the end-Cretaceous extinction closed out the age of non-avian dinosaurs entirely."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Qianzhousaurus hunted in a floodplain environment alongside an unusually diverse community of oviraptorosaurs - at least six species are known from the same formation, along with abundant egg clutches - which may have formed a significant part of its diet. Its long, narrow snout and slender teeth suggest fast, precise bites suited to smaller or more agile prey, rather than the bone-crushing bite associated with the deep skulls of Tyrannosaurus and Tarbosaurus.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Qianzhousaurus belongs to Alioramini, a lineage of long-snouted tyrannosaurids most closely related to Alioramus from Mongolia. Its existence, alongside deep-snouted tyrannosaurids in the same region and time window, shows that Late Cretaceous Asian ecosystems supported more than one basic tyrannosaurid body plan simultaneously, rather than a single dominant predator archetype.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"Is the long-snouted skull a distinct adult form, or a juvenile stage of a deep-snouted species?",
