  matters:"Qianzhousaurus shows how a specific, testable piece of anatomy - whether the skull bones were fused - could settle a genuine scientific question about tyrannosaur diversity, rather than leaving it as a matter of opinion. It is also a clear demonstration that Late Cretaceous Asia was not a one-predator ecosystem: long-snouted and deep-snouted tyrannosaurids appear to have lived side by side, doing different jobs.",
  fossilRecord:{
    knownFrom:"Holotype GM F10004 (nearly complete skull with lower jaw, cervical, dorsal and caudal vertebrae, shoulder girdles, partial pelvis, and most of the left hindlimb)",
    evidenceLevel:"Good",
    locality:"Ganzhou, Jiangxi Province, China",
    formation:"Nanxiong Formation",
    material:["Nearly complete skull","Cervical vertebrae","Dorsal vertebrae","Caudal vertebrae","Shoulder girdles","Partial pelvis","Hindlimb elements"],
    note:"The holotype was discovered by construction workers at an industrial park site in Ganzhou in 2010 and brought to the local museum before being formally described in 2014 by Lu Junchang and colleagues in Nature Communications. A detailed cranial redescription published in 2021 examined bone fusion and texture in depth, confirming a mature ontogenetic stage and directly addressing earlier speculation that the specimen might represent a juvenile of a different, deep-snouted species. Qianzhousaurus is the largest known member of Alioramini, a clade it shares with Alioramus from Mongolia. A smaller, deep-snouted tyrannosaurid, Asiatyrannus xui, was described from the same general region in 2024, raising the possibility of niche partitioning between contemporaneous predators of different skull shapes and sizes."
