  age:"~121-120 Ma (Early Cretaceous)", startMa:121, endMa:120, length:"~70-80 cm", mass:"~0.5-1 kg", place:"Liaoning; Hebei, China",
  img:"images/species/jeholornis.jpg",
  overview:"An early bird from the Jehol Biota of northeastern China, Jeholornis retained a long, bony, ancestral theropod-style tail closely resembling those of dromaeosaurids, while its shoulder and wing anatomy suggest it was capable of genuine powered flight. Its holotype preserved dozens of seeds in its crop, the first direct evidence of seed-eating in any Mesozoic bird, and roughly a hundred specimens are now known, making it one of the better-sampled birds of the Early Cretaceous.",
  insights:[
    ["A birdlike body with a dinosaur's tail","Jeholornis paired a long, bony tail with elongated prezygapophyses and chevrons - closely resembling the tails of dromaeosaurids such as <b>Velociraptor</b> - with advanced flight-capable shoulder anatomy, showing primitive and advanced features evolving <b>side by side in the same skeleton</b> rather than in sequence."],
    ["Fifty seeds and a stomach full of proof","The holotype preserved dozens of seeds clustered in its crop, giving <b>direct evidence of a seed-eating diet</b> in a Mesozoic bird, rather than an inference drawn only from tooth shape or jaw form."],
    ["A second line of digestive evidence, fifteen years on","A 2017 study identified <b>gastrolith masses</b> (swallowed gizzard stones) in five additional specimens, an independent line of evidence consistent with the seed-eating diagnosis first proposed from the crop contents in 2002."],
    ["A short tail and a long one, sharing the same lake","Confuciusornis, found in the same fossil beds, shows a short tail with ornamental feathers; Jeholornis instead kept a long, ancestral bony tail. Two very different tail strategies were <b>coexisting in the same ecosystem</b> at the same time."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Jeholornis most likely spent significant time on the ground or in low vegetation searching for seeds from cycads, ginkgo-like plants, or similar Early Cretaceous flora, consistent with its reduced dentition and deep, specialised jaw. Despite its basal position in early bird evolution, its robust pectoral girdle and wing anatomy indicate it was capable of powered flight rather than gliding alone.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Jeholornis sits among the earliest-diverging members of Avialae, positioned just crownward of Archaeopteryx in most analyses. Its retained long bony tail is a clearly ancestral, theropod-like feature, while its shoulder girdle and wing anatomy are comparatively advanced - a combination that illustrates early bird evolution was not a simple linear progression from primitive to modern, but a mosaic of traits changing at different rates.</p>",
  study:[
