    locality:"Jianchang and Chaoyang, Liaoning Province; Hebei Province",
    formation:"Jiufotang Formation; Yixian Formation",
    material:["Nearly complete skeletons","Long bony tails with feather impressions","Preserved seeds (crop contents)","Gastroliths","Skulls"],
    note:"Jeholornis prima was described in 2002 by Zhou Zhonghe and Zhang Fucheng in Nature, from a holotype (IVPP V13274) that preserved dozens of seeds clustered in the crop region - the first direct evidence of granivory in a Mesozoic bird. Two further species, J. palmapenis and J. curvipes, were named in 2012 and 2014 respectively based on differences in tail plumage and foot bone shape, though whether these represent truly distinct species or variation within J. prima remains debated among researchers. A 2017 study identified gastrolith masses in five specimens, providing an independent line of digestive evidence consistent with the original seed-eating diagnosis."
