  age:"~76.6-75.1 Ma (Late Cretaceous, Campanian)", startMa:76.6, endMa:75.1, length:"~8-9 m", mass:"~2-2.5 t", place:"Alberta, Canada",
  img:"images/species/gorgosaurus.jpg",
  overview:"A tyrannosaurid from the Campanian Dinosaur Park Formation of Alberta, Gorgosaurus is the best-represented tyrannosaurid in the fossil record, known from dozens of specimens spanning a near-complete growth series. It coexisted with the larger, more robust Daspletosaurus in the same formation, and is closely related to Albertosaurus - so closely that whether Gorgosaurus deserves its own genus at all remains an active point of disagreement.",
  insights:[
    ["The best-sampled tyrannosaur, not the most famous","With dozens of specimens spanning hatchling-adjacent juveniles to full adults, Gorgosaurus provides a <b>near-complete growth series</b> unmatched by almost any other tyrannosaurid, including Tyrannosaurus itself."],
    ["Sharing the top of the food chain","Gorgosaurus coexisted with Daspletosaurus in the same Alberta ecosystem at the same time - two large tyrannosaurids of similar size sharing one formation, a pattern proposed since 1970 to reflect <b>partitioning of prey between the two predators</b>, though direct evidence remains indirect."],
    ["One genus, or two?","Gorgosaurus and Albertosaurus are anatomically very similar, distinguished mainly by subtle skull and palate features. Some researchers treat Gorgosaurus as a <b>junior synonym of Albertosaurus</b>, while others maintain it as a distinct genus based on specific autapomorphies - a naming dispute rather than any doubt that the animals themselves existed."],
    ["A case of mistaken identity, corrected","A specimen long identified as a juvenile Daspletosaurus was reassessed in 2019 and reassigned to juvenile Gorgosaurus instead, once a properly diagnostic juvenile Daspletosaurus bone was found for direct comparison - a reminder that <b>identifying young tyrannosaurids is harder than identifying adults</b>."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Gorgosaurus was an apex predator of a lush floodplain environment along the edge of an inland sea, preying on the abundant ceratopsids and hadrosaurs of Campanian Alberta. Its comparatively light build and long limb proportions, similar to its close relative Albertosaurus, suggest a faster, more pursuit-capable predator than the heavier-skulled Daspletosaurus with which it shared its ecosystem.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Gorgosaurus belongs to Albertosaurinae, the more lightly built tyrannosaurid subfamily it shares with Albertosaurus, in contrast to the heavier-skulled Tyrannosaurinae subfamily that includes Daspletosaurus, Tyrannosaurus and Tarbosaurus. Its close relationship with Albertosaurus - the two are separated mainly by subtle skull and palate details - means Campanian Alberta hosted representatives of both major tyrannosaurid subfamilies at once, alongside each other in the same formation.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"Is Gorgosaurus a valid genus separate from Albertosaurus?",
     why:"The two are extremely similar in overall build and proportions, differing mainly in specific skull and palate details, so where to draw the genus boundary is a matter of ongoing judgement rather than a settled fact.",
     interps:[
       ["A distinct, valid genus","conf-moderate","Currie's 2003 analysis identified specific autapomorphies - including palatine and braincase differences - distinguishing Gorgosaurus from Albertosaurus, and this remains the current majority view."],
       ["A junior synonym of Albertosaurus","conf-low","Some researchers, including Carr and colleagues, argue the anatomical differences fall within the range expected of a single genus, making Gorgosaurus libratus effectively Albertosaurus libratus."]
     ]}
  ],
  matters:"Gorgosaurus shows that even one of the best-sampled dinosaurs in the world - with a fossil record most palaeontologists would envy - can still leave a basic question open: does this animal even belong in its own genus? The abundance of specimens has settled plenty about its growth and ecology, but not that.",
  fossilRecord:{
