  age:"~125-122 Ma (Early Cretaceous, Aptian)", startMa:125, endMa:122, length:"~1-1.2 m", mass:"~1-3 kg", place:"Liaoning, China",
  img:"images/species/sinornithosaurus.jpg",
  overview:"A small feathered dromaeosaurid from the Early Cretaceous Yixian Formation of Liaoning, Sinornithosaurus was among the first non-avian dinosaurs described with direct evidence of feathers. It became widely known in 2009 when a well-preserved skull led researchers to propose it was the first identified venomous dinosaur - a striking claim that a direct reassessment the following year found did not hold up under scrutiny.",
  insights:[
    ["An early witness to feathered dinosaurs","Sinornithosaurus was among the first non-avian dinosaurs formally described with <b>direct feather impressions</b>, helping establish early that feathers were not limited to the bird lineage."],
    ["A 'venomous dinosaur' headline, undone tooth by tooth","A 2009 study proposed Sinornithosaurus was venomous based on unusually long, grooved teeth and a skull cavity read as a venom gland pocket. A <b>2010 reassessment</b> directly challenged all three lines of evidence in the same journal."],
    ["The teeth weren't even that long","The 'elongated fangs' central to the venom claim turned out to be ordinary teeth that had <b>slipped partway out of their sockets</b> during fossil compression - a taphonomic artefact of preservation, not a real anatomical feature."],
    ["Real evidence of colour, right next to a claim that didn't hold up","Separate melanosome studies in 2010 and 2012 established genuine, independently supported evidence of body <b>colour patterning</b> - reddish-brown, yellow, black and grey - in the same animal, a useful contrast between a claim that held up and one that didn't."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Sinornithosaurus was a small, agile predator in the forested Jehol ecosystem of Early Cretaceous Liaoning, likely hunting small vertebrates and possibly birds. Its feathered covering, now known to have included patterned colouration, may have served roles in insulation and visual signalling alongside any role in movement, though its feathers were not suited to flight.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Sinornithosaurus belongs to Dromaeosauridae, close to the microraptorine radiation that also includes Microraptor in this collection. As one of the earliest well-preserved feathered non-avian theropods described, it contributed directly to establishing that feathers were an ancestral feature spread widely across theropod dinosaurs, not a trait confined to the lineage leading to birds.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"Was Sinornithosaurus venomous?",
     why:"The original 2009 case rested on three specific anatomical features, each of which a subsequent direct reassessment attempted to independently verify.",
     interps:[
       ["No - the supporting evidence does not hold up","conf-strong","A 2010 reassessment found the 'elongated' teeth were ordinary teeth displaced from their sockets during compression, and that grooved teeth are common and non-diagnostic across many theropods and dromaeosaurids generally."],
       ["Possibly, as a primitive trait retained from ancestral archosaurs","conf-low","The original authors' reply conceded the specific anatomical points but proposed venom might be a widely retained ancestral trait - a considerably weaker and less testable claim than the original."]
     ]}
  ],
  matters:"Sinornithosaurus is a clean demonstration of the scientific process working as intended. A striking claim generated real attention, but the direct scrutiny that is supposed to test such claims found that each piece of supporting evidence had a more mundane explanation, and the original claim was not sustained.",
  fossilRecord:{
    knownFrom:"Holotype IVPP V12811 (nearly complete skeleton with feather impressions) plus referred specimens including well-preserved skull material",
    evidenceLevel:"Good",
    locality:"Sihetun, western Liaoning Province",
    formation:"Yixian Formation (Jianshangou beds)",
    material:["Nearly complete skeleton (holotype)","Feather impressions","Skull material (referred specimens)","Melanosome-bearing feather tissue"],
    note:"Sinornithosaurus millenii was described in 1999 by Xu, Wang and Wu, among the earliest non-avian feathered dinosaurs formally named. A 2009 study (Gong, Martin, Burnham and Falk, PNAS) proposed a venom delivery system based on a well-preserved referred skull, citing elongated grooved teeth and a skull cavity interpreted as a venom gland pocket. A 2010 reassessment (Gianechini, Agnolin and Ezcurra), published in the same journal, examined the material directly and found the 'elongated' teeth had slipped from their sockets during compression and that grooved teeth are widespread among theropods rather than diagnostic of venom. The original authors' reply, in the same issue, conceded these specific points but proposed a broader, more speculative hypothesis that venom might be an ancestral archosaur trait retained in some lineages. Separate studies (Zhang et al., 2010; Li et al., 2012) independently established genuine colour patterning from preserved melanosomes."
