{
  id:"kulindadromeus", name:"Kulindadromeus", epithet:"K. zabaikalicus", pron:"koo-LIN-da-DROH-me-us",
  period:"jurassic", clade:"Basal neornithischian", diet:"herbivore",
  age:"~168-166 Ma (Middle Jurassic, Bathonian)", startMa:168, endMa:166, length:"~1-1.5 m", mass:"~10-20 kg", place:"Siberia, Russia",
  img:"images/species/kulindadromeus.jpg",
  overview:"A small basal ornithischian from the Middle Jurassic of Siberia, Kulindadromeus is preserved with an extraordinary range of skin coverings on a single skeleton: simple filaments on the head and thorax, larger scales on the tail and lower legs, and complex, branched feather-like structures on the upper limbs. Described in 2014 from hundreds of specimens at one site, it was the first strong evidence that feather-like integument was not confined to theropods, reopening the question of how early in dinosaur evolution such structures first appeared.",
  insights:[
    ["Three skin types, one animal","Kulindadromeus preserves <b>monofilaments, true scales, and complex branched feather-like structures</b> on different parts of the same body - a level of integumentary detail rarely seen in any dinosaur fossil, let alone an ornithischian."],
    ["The first strong ornithischian feather evidence","Before this description, feather-like coverings were documented almost exclusively in theropods. Kulindadromeus provided the clearest evidence that such structures also existed in <b>ornithischians</b>, the other major dinosaur lineage, raising the possibility that feather-like integument predates the theropod-ornithischian split entirely."],
    ["A site built for preservation","The Kulinda locality preserved six skulls and several hundred partial skeletons in fine-grained lake sediments, an unusually rich sample for a single ornithischian species and one that made this level of soft-tissue detail possible in the first place."],
    ["A discovery that reopened a question, not one that closed it","The original description itself noted that whether these branched structures are truly part of the same evolutionary lineage as theropod and bird feathers, or a separate, convergently evolved covering, <b>remains disputed</b> rather than settled by this find alone."]
  ],
  behaviour:"<p>Kulindadromeus was a small, bipedal, low-browsing herbivore living around Jurassic lakes in what is now southeastern Siberia, with teeth showing clear adaptations for processing plant material. Its mixed covering of filaments, feather-like structures, and scales likely served different functions across the body - insulation on the thorax and limbs, and more traditional protective scaling on the tail and lower legs exposed to ground contact.</p>",
  evolution:"<p>Kulindadromeus sits near the base of Neornithischia, the ornithischian lineage that would later diversify into ornithopods, ceratopsians, and other major herbivorous groups. Its mixed integument is central to an ongoing debate in dinosaur evolution: whether feather-like structures were present in the last common ancestor of all dinosaurs, later lost in most lineages and retained or elaborated in others, or whether ornithischian and theropod feather-like coverings evolved independently despite superficial similarity.</p>",
  study:[
    {q:"Are Kulindadromeus's feather-like structures evolutionarily related to theropod and bird feathers?",
     why:"Similar branched filamentous structures appear in both theropods and this basal ornithischian, but similarity alone does not prove shared ancestry rather than independent evolution.",
